    The Medina Hostel is a cheap and reasonably comfortable hostel in the medina of Tangier, Morocco. Since I have lived in Tangier and walk around the city, I had previously noticed this place. It may be a little difficult to locate at first, …
    The Medina Hostel is a cheap and reasonably comfortable hostel in the medina of Tangier, Morocco. Since I have lived in Tangier and walk around the city, I had previously noticed this place. It may be a little difficult to locate at first, but once you have found it and checked in, it should be easier. It is not far from the area called Sakaya, in the medina, and within walking distance of the Kasbah, the Petit Socco and Grand Socco, the Port of Tanger Ville and the Boulevard.
    I was in Tarifa during part of Ramadan and met some tourists where I stayed who were planning to visit Tangier on the FRS Ferry. When I asked them where they were staying, they told me The Medina Hostel.
    Apparently there is a free breakfast included and the interior rooms and bunk beds are clean, but there is no WiFi. Someone needs to tell the owner that one of his outside signs is misspelled as Midina. The correct spelling is Medina.

The hostel is tucked in in one of the passages in Medina, which seem very dodgy at night.     (Translated by Google) A medina is an urban agglomeration organized within the walls, that is, protected by a fortification. Medinas are usually the oldest parts of Arab cities, as there is always a new city outside these very fortifications.
    The tangle of streets, alleys and alleys, makes the medinas a real labyrinth, in which a simple walk sometimes becomes a real puzzle.
    Normally, in the center of the medinas there is a main square, from which several main avenues lead to the outside of the walls.

    These walls are often protected by watchtowers and opened by huge gates that lead in and out of the old medina into the city.
    In Morocco the best known are the medinas of Fez, Marrakech, Rabat, El Jadida, Essaouira, Casablanca, Chaouen, Asilah and Taroudant.
    Although the medinas show some visual confusion, it is not true that they do not follow certain urban orders and established rules.
    Medina of Tangier

    In the center of the medinas there is always a mosque, commonly called the Great Mosque.
    There are medinas that are organized according to ethnic groups or religions, the location of work activities, or a certain social or commercial hierarchy. Within the medinas there are several neighborhoods, markets and commercial areas and workshops.

    Route Marrakech And Essaouira 5 Days
    (Original)
    Una medina es una aglomeración urbana organizada dentro de las murallas, es decir, protegida por una fortificación. Por lo general, las medinas son las partes más antiguas de las ciudades árabes, ya que siempre hay una nueva ciudad fuera de estas mismas fortificaciones.
    La maraña de calles, callejuelas y callejones, hace de las medinas un auténtico laberinto, en el que un simple paseo se convierte a veces en un verdadero rompecabezas.
    Normalmente, en el centro de las medinas hay una plaza principal, de la que salen varias avenidas principales que conducen a la parte exterior de las murallas.

    A menudo, estas murallas están protegidas por torres de vigilancia y abiertas por enormes puertas que dan entrada y salida de la antigua medina a la ciudad.
    En Marruecos las más conocidas son las medinas de Fez, Marrakech, Rabat, El Jadida, Essaouira, Casablanca, Chaouen, Asilah y Taroudant.
    A pesar que las medinas muestran cierta confusión visual, no es cierto que no sigan determinadas ordenes urbanisticas y reglas establecidas.

    En el centro de las medinas siempre hay una mezquita, comúnmente llamada la Gran Mezquita.
    Hay medinas que están organizadas étnias o religiones, la ubicación de las actividades de trabajo, o una cierta jerarquía social o comercial. Dentro de las medinas hay varios barrios, mercados y áreas comerciales y talleres.

    Ancien Medina

    The walled Ancien Medina is entered through centuries-old gates, including Bab Al Bahr, which offers access to the ramparts for port views. The Tangier American Legation Museum traces local history, and there are displays of pottery and Roman relics in the Kasbah Museum, built around a courtyard. Alleys off Rue Siaghine are lined with shops selling rugs and spices, and lead to the landmark Grand Socco square.
